<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1297">Charles Stanley Reinhart,</rs> <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">For those in peril upon the sea</hi>, engraved by <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1591">Charles Roberts</rs>, in the Christmas issue of <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">The Graphic</hi> 1883, p. 30. <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_1255">Ill. 1255</rs>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="6" xml:id="note-t-6">
                            

<p>Van Gogh had been familiar with <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_899">Jules Breton</rs>’s poetry for some time. He had read the collection <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_29">Les champs et la mer</ref> </hi>(1875), which he had sent Theo in December 1875 (<ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let034.xml">see letters 34</ref> and <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let061.xml">61</ref>). Not long after this he copied out more poems from it for <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1306">Van Rappard</rs>. <ref xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" target="let435.xml">See letter 435</ref>.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="7" xml:id="note-t-7">
                            

<p>
      <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_371">Les humbles</ref> </hi>and <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_383">Promenades et intérieurs</ref></hi> (<hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Humble folk </hi>and <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Walks and interiors</hi>) are chapter headings in <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics"><ref target="biblio.xml#lit_368">Poesies de François Coppée</ref></hi> (Coppée 1880).</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
                        <note n="8" xml:id="note-t-8">
                            

<p><rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="person" ref="bio.xml#_1306">Van Rappard</rs> worked on his painting <hi xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" rend="italics">Sounding the vespers</hi> (present whereabouts unknown) in the winter of 1883-1884. <rs xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" type="artwork" ref="artwork.xml#ill_2120">Ill. 2120</rs>. The work was exhibited at the National Exhibition (Nationale Tentoonstelling) in Utrecht (cat. no. 103) in March 1884. See exhib. cat. Amsterdam 1974, p. 86, cat. no. 108.</p>
                        </note>
                        
                    
